g in the UK as the one issue I am raising have wide public significance. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This letter focus on the specific issue of Dame Julie repeatedly ignoring the several internal complaints I made regarding the exceedingly poor quality of service I have received from her staff over the past one year. In total, my MP made 3 referrals containing 6 separate cases, none of which were properly dealt with by Dame Julie and her staff. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">My high profile case about Abuse and Negligence in the NHS was referred by a Senior MP (former Minister of London and Minister of State for Environment) but the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman's staff stubbornly refused to investigate. I have no money to launch a judicial review to overturn their wrong decision, so am stuck with their wrong decision (I did lodge an internal appeal but the result was even more unfair). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However, during the past year, I made several Internal Complaints about the discriminatory treatment and appallingly poor quality of service received from their staff. On all occasions they persistently refused to investigate those internal complaints and gave vexatious reasons for their refusals. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I am a person with multiple disabilities and multiple minority identities protected by the Equality Act 2010, the way I was treated by the Ombudsman's staff infringed and violated my rights and dignity (for instance, the reckless words from their acting assistant director in a hurtful letter and then ignored my response). </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">My long-standing high profile case is receiving attention at national level from press and media, but before publication, I feel that the Chair of the PASC (Public Administration Select Committee) needs to intervene and set the record straight. Just think, if a highly qualified senior professional who was published and won the respect of the Prime Minister can't get any justice from the Ombudsman, what chance is there for the rest of the 62 million people in the UK? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">My high profile case was part of the Clwyd-Hart Review commissioned by the Prime Minister, launched by the Health Secretary and published by the Department of Health in October 2013. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I am aware that you are a Senior MP with 16 years experience. Being a Registered Counsellor, I am aware that you are the Vice-President of Combat Stress (we have a lot to talk about when we meet). </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As you can see, I am not raising concerns of a personal nature, but I am expressing my professional opinion (in the past I have held senior positions in the health sector including NHS) that the Ombudsman's Office appears to be on the edge of "not fit for purpose". </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I have received sympathetic replies from the UK Chief Hospital Inspector newly appointed by David Cameron, but he has no power to intervene the Ombudsman's Office, only the Chair of the PASC (Public Administration Select Committee) has the jurisdiction and power to look into the aforementioned matter. I have also applied to work for the Care Quality Commission (CQC) as a Hospital Inspector. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I should be grateful if we can have a short meeting in your House of Commons office to discuss the aforementioned concerns that have wide public significance. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I look forward to hearing from you and your colleagues.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">10 December 2013 </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>